        "excerpt": "Jesus heard that they had put him out, and finding him, He said, \"Do you believe in the Son of Man?\"",
        "body": "Verse 35 is the pastoral center of the chapter. *Jesus heard that they had put him out, and finding him…* The Shepherd hears about the sheep cast out and goes looking. The contrast to v. 34 is total: the religious establishment cast him out; the One they claim to serve seeks him out. The verse foreshadows the Good Shepherd discourse of chapter 10 (10:3, 4, 14) — Jesus knows His own by name and calls them out.\n\nThe question — *do you believe in the Son of Man?* — is the gospel question. *Son of Man* (*ho huios tou anthrōpou*) is the title Jesus most often uses of Himself, drawn from Daniel 7:13-14 — the heavenly figure who comes on the clouds and receives universal dominion and worship. The man does not yet know the title's referent; his question (*who is He, Lord, that I may believe in Him?*) is honest. The Greek *kurie* here is on the edge between courteous *sir* and confessional *Lord* — and after v. 38, it is clearly the latter.\n\nJesus' answer (v. 37) is a deliberate echo of His self-disclosure to the Samaritan woman (4:26): *you have both seen Him, and He is the one who is talking with you*. The verb *seen* is theologically loaded — the man whose eyes were opened only hours ago is now told that the One who opened them is here, in his sight. Sight and confession converge in a single moment.\n\nThe man's response is the cleanest confession in the chapter: *Lord, I believe*. And he *worshiped Him* (*prosekynēsen autō*). *Proskuneō* is the verb of worship offered to God — used in this Gospel of true worship of the Father (4:20-24) and elsewhere refused by Peter (Acts 10:25-26) and by angels (Revelation 19:10; 22:9). Jesus receives it without correction. The healed man's worship is implicit Trinitarian christology in narrative form: he worships Jesus, and Jesus accepts what only God may accept. The progression — *the man called Jesus* (v. 11) → *a prophet* (v. 17) → *from God* (v. 33) → *Lord, I believe* with worship (v. 38) — is John's portrait of how faith grows under pressure.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Eurō* (finding, v. 35) — Jesus actively seeks and finds. *Proskuneō* (worshiped, v. 38) — to prostrate before, to do obeisance. In John, the word is used of true worship (4:20-24); its application to Jesus here is a christological declaration in narrative form. *Pisteuō* (believe) is in the present tense in both v. 35 and v. 38 — ongoing trust, not a single instant."
